<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[317,1270,1537,1789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
– Described on the basis of a single male specimen from European 
<collectingCountry box="[562,626,1652,1673]" name="Russia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Yaroslavskaya district). New to the fauna of 
<collectingCountry box="[1064,1126,1652,1673]" name="South Korea" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Korea</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[317,1270,1537,1789]" lastBlockId="7.[317,1271,436,1782]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
– My five Korean females match the short description of the male (
<bibRefCitation author="TOBIAS, V. I." box="[837,1011,1681,1702]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 309" refId="ref23738" refString="TOBIAS, V. I. (1986) 27. ordo Hymenoptera, family Braconidae. (2.). Key to the Insects of the European Part of the USSR III. Hymenoptera 5: 1 - 309. [In Russian]" type="journal article" year="1986">Tobias 1986: 212</bibRefCitation>
), additional features are as follows: (1) antenna somewhat longer than body and with 33–35 antennomeres, distal flagellomeres 1.4 times as long as broad; (2) 
<emphasis box="[604,656,1739,1760]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">m–cu</emphasis>
more or less antefurcal; (3) first tergite evenly broadening posteriorly, somewhat longer than broad behind, longitudinally rugose; (4) hypygium pointed, ovipositor sheath as long as hind tarsomeres 1–4 combined; (5) tegula yellow, parategula vivid yellow; (6) metasoma brown, first tergite black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
